=== CORS ANALYSIS ===

Next.js API routes (app/api/):
- ZERO explicit CORS headers set in any API route handler
- No cors middleware applied to API routes
- proxy.ts has CORS logic but is DEAD CODE (not used as middleware)
- Default behavior: Next.js API routes do NOT set CORS headers, meaning:
  - Same-origin requests work fine
  - Cross-origin requests are blocked by browser (no Access-Control-Allow-Origin)
  - This is RESTRICTIVE by default — GOOD for security

Supabase Edge Functions:
- 14 functions use Access-Control-Allow-Origin: '*' — HIGH RISK
  - These are callable from any origin
  - Includes: metrics-exporter, grade-ai, ai-course-create, webhook-dispatch, email-dispatch, etc.
  - public-submit uses origin allowlist — GOOD

Netlify Functions:
- file-return.ts: Access-Control-Allow-Origin: '*' — HIGH (tax filing endpoint)
- refund-tracking.ts: Access-Control-Allow-Origin: '*' — MEDIUM (public tracking)

server/index.ts:
- Line 20: res.header('Access-Control-Allow-Origin', '*') — HIGH if this runs in production

FINDINGS:
1. Next.js API routes: Restrictive by default (no CORS headers) — GOOD
2. Supabase functions: Wildcard CORS on 14 functions — MEDIUM-HIGH
3. Netlify functions: Wildcard CORS on tax filing endpoint — HIGH
4. proxy.ts CORS logic is dead code — CONTRADICTION with any claim it provides CORS protection
